Eigenlijk een zangeres die aan mij voorbij is gegaan. Als toentertijd al niet al te jonge witte Nederlandse man was ik misschien ook niet helemaal (meer) de doelgroep. Ik hoorde dit nummer voor 't eerst bewust in een filmpje hier op het immense YT, waarin een nog 1-jarig klein New Yorkse meisje onder leiding van haar liefhebbende vader zich ontworstelde aan de moeizame start die zij in het leven had gemaakt. Aangezien ik zelf toen ook niet al te best in mijn vel zat, bleek zij opeens een soort van inspiratie voor mij. Op wonderbaarlijke wijze kreeg ik contact met de vader, en we mailden. We hebben elkaar een keer gezien in 's werelds boeiendste stad, New York City, en dat was met z'n zessen heel gezellig (inclusief 2 partners, en een hele aardige huisvriend die zelfs Nederlands sprak). En hoewel het mailcontact met haar vader vervolgens helaas/grotesk ten einde kwam, kan ik naar dit prima, (op een prettige wijze) wat lompe liedje nog goed luisteren. En hoop ik maar, dat het met die dochter, inmiddels een echte puber van 14, nog steeds wat beter gaat. Ik gun je het aller-, allerbeste!

I remember, as a kid, being in awe of this video when it dropped. I watched it over and over. It was like no other media I had been exposed to before. It had the sexiness of some of Gwen Stefani's music videos from around that era, but leaned WAY more into it's avant-garde elements. Those big edited eyes and that pink wig, the diamonds hanging in place, whatever the hell that circle gear was she was wearing (shout out to when she wore it to perform on SNL and it smacked Gaga's head, and she had to pretend not to notice), the POLAR BEAR CAPE, the freaky dancing in the opening of the song... And god, the last few seconds of her laying in the burnt bed with her lover's skeleton, tiddies going full sparkler mode. Iconic.  Despite her immense popularity, at that time it seems like she was often spoken of as if her work was 'too weird', but man, it was, and continues to be some special kind of art. I can only see now how deeply her music, videos, and overall public persona inspired so many unexpected aspects of my life.

"Gangnam Style" was the first YouTube video to reach a billion hits. That's sort of unfair to the American slant of the video-sharing website because of the vast, basically untapped, population of countries neighboring South Korea. Few other videos from that part of the world enjoy massive amounts of hits. The video, because of its hooked beats and its charming and refreshingly unique, even dorky, dancing by its singer, the K-Pop rapper Psy, went crazy-viral. If you adjust world population densities with consistent sources of world music, nothing could compare to Lady Gaga's "Bad Romance" video. It blew everything else out of the water. Its influence on world culture went viral. It has been covered by countless singers. It has been converted into marching band music and at least one Bach-style fugue. And it's a tune that has been adopted onstage by another charming entity: a great big group of Chinese senior citizens. "Bad Romance" is in a league of its own. It's witty and freaky at the same time. It's high fashion. It's "desperate." It's filled with tons of product placement. Its stripper- and "Thriller"-based choreography is unequalled. The entire video is shot on an all-white bathhouse set with a drop ceiling (saved a lot of money). It's a lovely tribute to the late Alexander McQueen. And it's a sublime adjunct to an amazing song by an amazing songstress, who, after all these years, shows no signs of abatement.

I vividly remember receiving a very bad beating from my father when this song came out. I got home from school and my sibling saw lady gaga as my phone's wallpaper, and since they had an inkling of my sexuality back then, they always see to it that I get 'straightened out' whenever I act too effeminate or what have you. I remember running away from our house and getting on my bicycle to go to my nana's house and cool off a bit. I was 13 at the time, and my escape was LG and her music. My nana gave me 15 Philippine Pesos (around 30 US cents) to go to a computer shop and play games with my cousins. that was the day that I got to listen to this song. let's just say that after bopping to this song, I kind of gained guts and courage to not give a fcck about the beatings and shit my dad gave me for being different. I am now 28, a proud transwoman living life to the fullest, and I know that the song is a major bop, but I can't help but cry listening to this today.
